solution.p:
The distance  r  to the center of the square will be same for the four charges.

	r =   \frac{5}{\sqrt{2}} \ \mu\text{m}=  3.54 \ \mu\text{m}.

The magnitudes of the electric field from the four charges will be

	 E_P^{\textrm{by A}} \amp  = 9\times 10^9 \times \frac{3\times 10^{-9}}{\left(3.54\times 10^{-6}\right)^2} = 2.15\times 10^{12}\ \textrm{N/C}
	 E_P^{\textrm{by B}} \amp = E_P^{\textrm{by A}} \times \frac{4}{3} = 2.87\times 10^{12}\ \textrm{N/C} 
	 E_P^{\textrm{by C}} \amp = E_P^{\textrm{by A}} \times \frac{6}{3} = 4.31 \times 10^{12}\ \textrm{N/C}
	 E_P^{\textrm{by D}} \amp  = E_P^{\textrm{by A}} \times \frac{9}{3} = 6.46 \times 10^{12}\ \textrm{N/C}

sidebyside.p:
The directions of these electric fields are  shown in the figure. With the choice of the  x  and  y  coordinates shown in the figure we find the  x - and  y -components of the net electric field at the center to be

	 E_{x} \amp  = \left( 2.87 - 6.46 \right)\times 10^{12}\ \textrm{N/C}
		 \amp = -3.59\times 10^{12}\ \textrm{N/C}
	 E_{y} \amp  = \left( 4.31 - 2.15 \right)\times 10^{12}\ \textrm{N/C}
	 	 \amp = = 2.16\times 10^{12}\ \textrm{N/C}

solution.p:
The net electric field will be a vector sum of the electric fields from each charge. Let us denote the electric field of  +q  by  \vec E_1  and that of  -q  by   \vec E_2 .  We can write the Cartesian components of these electric fields at P as follows.

	 E_{1x} \amp =  \frac{k\:q\:x}{ \left[ x^2 + (y-d/2)^2 \right]^{3/2}  }
	 E_{1y} \amp =  \frac{k\:q\:(y-d/2)}{ \left[x^2 + (y-d/2)^2 \right]^{3/2}  }
	 E_{2x} \amp =  \frac{-k\:q\:x}{ \left[x^2 + (y+d/2)^2 \right]^{3/2}  }
	 E_{2y} \amp =  \frac{-k\:q\:(y+d/2) }{ \left[x^2 + (y+d/2)^2 \right]^{3/2}  }

The Cartesian components of the net electric field  \vec E  at the field point P will be

	  E_x \amp = E_{1x} + E_{2x},
	  E_y \amp = E_{1y} + E_{2y}.

From these we will get the magnitude and direction as angle as

	  E \amp = \sqrt{E_x^2 + E_y^2},
	  \theta \amp = \tan^{-1}\left( \dfrac{E_y}{E_x} \right).
